post_text: You should have received a call this week informing you of our enrollment days. If your student was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma’s Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income.

The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu<mailto:okpromise@osrhe.edu

post_text: Nick Sayegh received the honor of being selected as a 2020 US Presidental Scholar. He is one of only two scholars chosen from Oklahoma. We are so proud of his accomplishments! post_text:
As much as we hate to do this, we have to consider the safety and health of our staff members and our students/families:

It is with great sadness that we are announcing the temporary stoppage of our food preparation and delivery service to our students effective today April 6th. With the continued recommendations for separation issued to our communities by the CDC, Oklahoma's Governor and the Mayor of OKC and our concern for the safety of our students, staff, parents, and the communities we serve, we feel we must stop and allow the shelter in place guidelines to have time to take the full effect that they are intended for. We will hope to restart this service as soon as this pandemic is controled or eradicated and our students families are able to return to normal socialization. Thank you for your understanding during this very difficult time for us all. Please stay safe.
text:
As much as we hate to do this, we have to consider the safety and health of our staff members and our students/families:

It is with great sadness that we are announcing the temporary stoppage of our food preparation and delivery service to our students effective today April 6th. With the continued recommendations for separation issued to our communities by the CDC, Oklahoma's Governor and the Mayor of OKC and our concern for the safety of our students, staff, parents, and the communities we serve, we feel we must stop and allow the shelter in place guidelines to have time to take the full effect that they are intended for. We will hope to restart this service as soon as this pandemic is controled or eradicated and our students families are able to return to normal socialization. Thank you for your understanding during this very difficult time for us all. Please stay safe.

post_text:
This is why we do what we do:

This story was shared by one of our bus drivers today.

All, today while driving our food lunch delivery buses, one of our drivers told me that at one of the stops a small girl came to bus and said Mrs. Bus Driver I am so glad that you came because I am so hungry. Food service gave her the meals and the girl said wait here Mrs. Bus Driver. The child ran back to the house and came out with two pictures that she had colored…one for the driver and one for the food service worker. They told the girl they would be back again tomorrow at the same time.

THAT’S WHAT IT IS ALL ABOUT….. We are running 8 buses plus a special needs bus. Delivered 800 meals the first day and increasing each day. THANK YOU TO OUR JETS BUS DRIVERS, OUR JETS FOOD SERVICE AND SECURITY STAFF THAT ARE WORKING DURING THIS DIFFICULT TIME!

Starting Monday, March 23, our child nutrition staff will prepare a sack lunch and a sack breakfast for students aged 0-18. The food will be loaded onto buses and we will run a modified route with modified stops. We will be able to feed everyone under the age of 18 who are at the stops. Since we have no idea how many students will be at the stops the routes are subject to change. Buses will leave the main campus at 10:30 am and should arrive at the indicated time on the attached routes. We will of course adjust routes as needed as we figure out the numbers of students that will be at each route.

We are posting updates on our website as well. For the route information and other information please check the site.

We are cancelling school tomorrow, Friday, March 13, 2020 so our support staff can be proactive in cleaning and sanitizing our schools. We are also cancelling all after school extracurricular activities effective tomorrow, March 13, 2020. We want to reassure you that we have not received a reported case of the Coronavirus at Western Heights and want to keep it that way. We will continue to keep you updated as we learn more from the State Department of Education or Oklahoma County Health officials. If we do need to close school for any reason in the future, closures will be reported via news outlets, social media, and the district notification system. Thank you.

Please see attached letter that will go home to families today. Both Spanish and English available.

post_text: We have had a water line break at the High School that is affecting the coolant system, which will not be fixed until later today, so air is down. The new employee daycare at Western Heights is quickly coming together. We are hosting an Open House on Friday, July 26 at 6:00pm. We would love for you to stop by and check it out.

With that said, there are a few required items that we are still needing. If you have any items lying around that you would be happy to donate, please either drop them off at the administration building (ask that they shove them in my office), or email Jana Pennock, our new childcare director(jana.k.pennock@westernheights.k12.ok.us), or call/text her (405-420-7718) and she'll work out a way to pick up the items. She has an extensive list of needed items. Please reach out to her about it, but she can always use various toys/infant equipment, and indoor and outdoor play equipment.
-Hayden Roberts

post_text: The senior class sponsors will host a senior breakfast for the 2019 graduating class. At the breakfast, each student has their name drawn for a gift. These gifts often range from a $10 gift card to a mini fridge. The gifts are something that will help them as they leave high school. It could be a 7-11 card for gas, a basket of dorm room stuff, basket of laundry stuff, or anything that they could use after they graduate! If you know of a business or someone who would like to donate, please email: llcastrop@whisd.org or call at 405-623-1299.

Major Ed Pulido was part of a convoy going into hostile territory when they hit a road side bomb. He sustained serious injuries that not only affected him physically but also mentally. He started Warriors For Freedom to educate people on the stressors of war and help people understand the importance of peer to peer support. #ThriverThursday

post_text: At the end of October, 32 of our high school girls participated in the Women in Science conference. The students experienced dozens of hands-on STEM activities, and met representatives from universities and corporations to learn more about pursuing careers in the science fields. They also met panelists who shared stories about their experiences with being a women leader in STEM-related fields such as engineering, technology, aviation, zoology, and medicine.

All returning students (who were here last year) will enroll starting Aug 10. You will go to the site of your youngest child and the enrollment dates are Aug 10 (8-3) Aug 13 (8-3, 4:30-7:30) and Aug 14 (8-3, 4:30-7:30). Please bring proof of residence in form of utility bill or lease agreement.

Hope this clears up any confusion.

post_text: Friday, at the very end of the school day (last period) two 9th grade students reported to district officials that another 9th grade student verbally threatened to bring a gun to school on Monday the 12th of March. District officials immediately contacted the Oklahoma City Police Department and an intensive investigation of the incident was initiated. The student who threatened to bring the gun to school will not be allowed to return to school. It is very reassuring to know that we had to two very courageous young students step forward to let us know of the threat. We are very proud that these students contacted school officials, and we would like to thank the Oklahoma City Police Department for their quick and very effective response to the threat. Joe Kitchens, Superintendent
